==English==

===Etymology===
From late Latin ''[[encliticus]]'', from Greek [[εγκλιτικος]], from [[εγκλινειν]] ‘lean on’, from [[ἐν-]] + [[κλίνειν]] ‘to lean, incline’.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɪnˈklɪtɪk/}}, {{IPA|/ɛnˈklɪtɪk/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{linguistics}} A [[clitic]] which joins with the preceding word. In English, the [[possessive]] '''[['s]]''' is an example.

